<br>
The difference is bigger than most people think, because the many edges a wizard has add up.<br>
<br>
Lets take 2 well geared casters, and stack them up:<br>
<br>
The Wizard nukes using SoS, a 4.28 ratio nuke that does 267.32 chain cast DPS.<br>
The -10 resist mod makes an additional small difference -- 2% for a lowball guess.<br>
<br>
The Mage nukes using Sun Vortex, a 3.92 ratio nuke that does 180.23 chain cast DPS.<br>
<br>
Mana regen:<br>
The wizard has 4 different mana regen lines.<br>
<br>
The familiar line stacks with everything, and tops off at 8 mana per tick.<br>
<br>
Two harvest lines (AA and non) give 6 and 3.25 mana per tick respectively.<br>
<br>
The epic/forceshield line doesn't stack with beastlord mana regen, and gives 3 mana per tick.  (BST buff gives 9)<br>
<br>
The Mage has a 6 mana per tick self buff, that does not stack with the cabbage line of druid mana regen buffs.  (DRU line gives 8)<br>
<br>
Using mod rods mages can manage another 7 mana per tick (the damage is small enough to be ignored).<br>
<br>
Cannipet techniques can give them significant mana regen at the cost of their pet's DPS.<br>
<br>
Both can get a KHF self-buff.<br>
<br>
KEI can be assumed in XP groups and VoQ in raids.<br>
<br>
Total self manaregen from buffs/spells: About 39 for wiz, and 32 for mage.<br>
Total raid manaregen from buffs/spells: 66 for wiz and 49 for mage<br>
<br>
(on a raid, both classes have a mod rod, and neither pays for it).<br>
<br>
Another 44 mana from horse/FT/MC for each player is availiable.<br>
<br>
Criticals:<br>
Wizards get SCF 3 SCFM 3 and FoMM 3.  Crit rates of 20%<br>
Mages get SCF 3 and Fury of Magic 3.  Crit rates of 10%<br>
<br>
Foci: Level playing field.  Lets go on the uber side -- 25% mana savings and 25% damage add.<br>
<br>
Spec: Assume both have SCM 3 and the correct Spec for their nuke.<br>
<br>
Ok, now given the above, what is the DPS gap?<br>
<br>
Chain cast DPS:<br>
Wizard: 355.5<br>
Mage: 226.1<br>
<br>
That isn't that interesting, unless the fight is very short.  For longer fights:<br>
<br>
Damage per REAL mana for wizards: 11.39<br>
Damage per REAL mana for mages: 9.64<br>
2% more resists for mages drops their DpRM to 9.44<br>
<br>
So, sustained DPS for mages (raid buffs) is: 146.32  (64% of chain cast)<br>
Sustained DPS for wizards (raid buffs) is: 208.82  (59% of chain cast)<br>
<br>
Sustained DPS gap between wizards and mages on raids: 62.5 DPS.<br>
<br>
Sustained DPS for mages (xp group) is: 119.57 (53% of chain cast)<br>
Sustained DPS for wizards (xp group) is: 157.56 (44% of chain cast)<br>
<br>
Sustained DPS gap between wizards and mages in xp groups: 38 DPS<br>
<br>
50% uptime group (using the strictest definition of uptime):<br>
Mage hits 226.1 (chain cast limit)<br>
Wizard hits 315.1<br>
<br>
This results in a DPS gap of 89.<br>
<br>
50% uptime is actually a reasonable approximation of most xp groups (see the damage over time graph thread above for justification).<br>
<br>
Alternative Nukes:<br>
Wizard Iceflame + Ancient Ice: 12.81 (with a pres of solusk item)<br>
Wizard Iceflame + IceSpear: Less DPS than SoS with ideal foci.<br>
FoT: 9.47 (with a pres of solusk item) plus has issues with being blocked.<br>
<br>
The alternatives actually help the wizard more than the mage.<br>
<br>
Malo would help mage's keep up with a wizard's nuking DPS.  Cannipet techniques are made pretty obsolete -- the mage actually runs into issues with not running oom while chain nuking during engagement.  Cannipet looks like a post-rez recovery technique at this stage of the game.<br>
<br>
So, after all this work, I am forced to conclude:<br>
<br>
Mages and wizards in good gear, with good AAs, at L 65, actually look relatively balanced.<br>
